            <h5 class="blogsubject" style="">Politics</h5> 
            <h4 class="blogtitle" style="">The Karnataka Election Field Diary of Sachin Reddy</h4>
            
            <div class="bloglinks" style=""><!--By <a>Subhash Chabra</a> & <a>Amitabh Tiwari</a>--></div>
            <div class="blogtext">
                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">26 March 2018</h5>
                <p>JD(S), if allied with Congress for 2018, will be the biggest loser of Karnataka. This will be it’s last serious election. Of course it will certainly help Cong to retain power & will keep BJP out of power, but in next elections, state will become truly bipolar!</p>
                <p>Not to mention, the party will split before elections and half of its ranks & files will migrate to BJP! BJP will grow in a big way in south Karnataka if this happens!</p>
                <p>Updated seat ratings from Tumkur district:</p>
                <p>UPGRADE:</p>
                <p>Gubbi & Turuvekere from toss-up to Lean BJP</p>
                <p>DOWNGRADE:</p>
                <p>Net positive for BJP since Dec-Jan</p>
                <p>Overall,</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>BJP 5</li>
                    <li>Con 2</li>
                    <li>JDS 2</li>
                    <li>Toss-up  2</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Banthanal Mutt & Babaleshwar Mutt have declared open war against M B Patil & have vowed to defeat him! More than half of all Lingayats in this AC follow these 2 mutts. On the other side, Mate Mahadevi & Jayamrutyunjaya Swami of Kudalasangama have thrown their weight behind Patil!</p>
                <p>M B Patil has apparently got negative response from Thontadarya Mutt and Chitradurga Brihanmutt to openly endorse him and to direct their subsidiaries to work for him in his constituency! Is these Mutts remain neutral, going gets tough for Patil. Only his 100 Crores can save him!</p>
                <p>After much pursuation, I’ve got voteshare details from the poll (Independent group) that I quoted last week. This is what the poll gives</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>BJP 35.3%</li>
                    <li>Con 35.1%</li>
                    <li>JDS 17.6%</li>
                    <li>Oth  12%</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>With almost similar vote spread as in past 3 assembly elections, this will easily translate into simple majority for BJP!</p>
                
                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">25 March 2018</h5>
                <p>Stand by for something big from Karnataka. Hint: it’s about a promise that I had made few days ago</p>
                <p>Concluded the data analysis of a small snap poll from Bijapur, Bagalkot & Dharwad districts about Lingayat religion issue that I’ve conducted. Will tweet the findings in this tweet series. Do follow the thread for more insights</p>
                <p>On Random sampling basis, responses were collected from 300 respondents belonging to Lingayat/Veerashaiva community from 3 districts of Bijapur, Bagalkot & Dharwad. The raw data has been weighed to match the gender & caste-wise breakdown of the actual Lingayat population</p>
                <p>Caste composition of the poll sample that was taken is as in the given chart. Overall composition of Lingayat-Veerashaiva population is somewhat similar to this. There is however, huge difference between composition in North, Central & South Karnataka districts</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture49.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <p>Of this, Jangama, Sadaru and many Panchamasali &  Ganiga ardently follow Panchapeethas(Kashi, Ujjaini, Rambhapuri, Kedara, Shreeshaila) which are vehemently opposed to the move by state govt to separate Lingayats from Hindu religion & grant them minority status!</p>
                <p>In reality, there is no clarity as to which of the many sub sects identify themselves as Lingayat and which of them as Veerashaiva on the lines of the divide that the politicians have tried to engineer. In fact, most respondents say they are Veerashaiva-Lingayats!</p>
                <p>When asked, if they identify themselves as belonging to a Lingayat religion which is distinct from the Hindu religion, Only 12% said ‘Yes’! This must spell doom for those who calculated political gains in dividing a pious community of Karnataka</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture48.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <p>The support for granting independent religion status for Lingayats in a population of exclusively Lingayat respondents is meagre 18%! Although further research was not possible due to lack of resources,  at the outset, most supporters of the move were traditional INC voters!</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture47.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <p>Among various sub sects, slightly higher proportion of Panchamasalis(Vinay Kulkarni) and Kuduvokkaliga(MBPatil) Lingayats expressed support for independent religion status for Lingayats. Support for the same is almost non existent among Jangamas and Ganigas(BSY’s caste)</p>
                <p>Updated seat-ratings from Coastal Karnataka:</p>
                <p>UPGRADE: Mangalore city(S) from toss-up to Lean BJP, Puttur from Lean BJP to Safe BJP</p>
                <p>Outlook of all the seats in Udupi & North Canara district remain unchanged as <a href="https://twitter.com/snsachinnandu/status/949263483329118209?s=21" target="_blank">here</a> …</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture46.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                
                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">24 March 2018</h5>
                <p>In Belgaum south, sitting MLA Sambhaji Patil of MES has become very unpopular outside the ardent Marathi circles. BJP’s former MLA Abhay Patil is clear front runner to retake this seat. Cong will take the Muslim votes and maybe some Kannada votes but not enough to win!</p>
                <p>In Belgaum north, a tripolar battle has firmed up between BJP, Cong and MES. Cong sitting MLA Firoz Sait has a neutral image. Former Belgaum Mayor Renu Killekar & ex MLA Manohar Kinekar are competing for MES ticket. Despite a dozen aspirants & confusion about candt, BJP has edge!</p>
                
                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">23 March 2018</h5>
                <p>There is near total consolidation of STs behind BJP in Karnataka. It is true from Bellary to Gulbarga to Belgaum to Canara to Mysore! Expect 70-75% of all STs to go with the BJP. Cong’s efforts to project sugar barons Jarakiholis as successful leaders of STs has failed miserably!</p>
                
                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">22 March 2018</h5>
                <p>Bijapur city is all set to witness an epic battle. BJP’s ex MLA Appu Pattanashetty is readying ground to get ticket to take on Cong sitting MLA Maqbool Bagwan. Ex BJP man & former central minister BR Yatnal is also an aspirant- if BJP won’t give him ticket, might fight as ind!</p>
                <p>Several issues/people hv put a hold on Yatnal’s reentry into BJP. He’s an influential Lingayat leader, can influence outcome in 3-4 ACs! If he fights as an independent from Bijapur city, the contest will be very tough and the hugely unpopular Cong MLA might even scrape through!</p>
                <p>In Nagthana AC next door, the contest is again tripolar between sitting Cong MLA Raju Alagur(quite popular), JDS’ Devendra Chauhan & District BJP president & BSY loyalist Vitthal Katakadonda. Right hand Dalits, Lambanis & Lingayats will decide the victor. I see a slight BJP edge</p>
                <p>In Tikota, after having initial hiccups, irrigation minister and the chief conspirator of Lingayat movement, M B Patil has consolidated some ground over the past few months. BJP’s Vijugouda Patil who narrowly lost to MBP in 2013 on JDS ticket is putting up a spirited fight!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">21 March 2018</h5>
                <p>Kunigal has turned into a proper tripolar contest. Sitting MLA D Nagarajaiah of JDS will test his luck once again against his brother D Krishnakumar of BJP who had come 2nd in 08 & 13 and hence has sympathy in his favour this time around. 20k strong Lingayats are also with him!</p>
                <p>Two times former Cong MLA from Kunigal, B B Ramaswamy Gowda had come 3rd in 2013 behind BJP’s Krishna Kumar. Reason enough for DKShi brothers to pounce upon this constituency to install their cronies here. Two of their relatives are competing strongly with Gowda for Cong ticket.</p>
                <p>With 3-way split of the strong Vokkaliga vote bloc, Lingayats are likely to consolidate behind BJP. 30k+ strong Muslim voters will play a crucial role if OBC votes do not consolidate behind anyone. Overall, Kunigal is a very tough seat to predict as of now!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">20 March 2018</h5>
                <p>For all those interested in Karnatka elections, here’s a detailed breakdown of vote contributions of various vote blocs of the state. I have compiled this after going through authoritative & authentic literature. RT
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture2.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                </p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">19 March 2018</h5>
                <p>Although individually, the smaller OBC castes may not be big vote blocs. But together, Kumbara, Vishwakarma, Nekara, Yadava/Golla, Uppara, Eediga, Mogaveera, Kabbaliga, Balija, Maratha/Devadiga together constitute ~20% of the electorate in KA. All of them are pissed with Cong!</p>
                <p>Traditionally, BJP takes nearly 50% of these OBC/MBC/EBC votes. Which translates to roundly 10% of all all the votes. But with a peak anger against Cong & especially Sidramaiah, BJP might take time at least 70% of all these votes! Will be a big boost to  overall picture!</p>
                <p>Assuming a slightly lower turnout among these castes, BJP might end up with 12-13% of voteshare from just BCs. Assuming a lower than usual share from Lingayats of around 10%, 4% from STs, 4% from UCs, 6% from SCs and 1% from others, BJP is on course to poll 34-36% of total votes!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">18 March 2018</h5>
                <p>KA under @siddaramaiah has transformed into Gunda Raj. Even cops r beaten up, threatened & abused by both ruling class & mafia, commit suicides/get killed! Imagine the plight of common man. @RLR_BTM & before him @thekjgeorge have been the most incompetent HMs KA has ever seen!</p>
                <p>Lol. A R Krishnamurthy is son of A Rachayya, political guru of Siddaramaiah who is taking him in despite dissent from within Cong to honour his words to his Guru. Kollegal already has Cong MLA! Plus ARK was not announced as BJP candt. Also, he’s not the ONLY strong leader for BJP</p>


