                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">16 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>#KarnatakaElections</p>
                <p>Districts where BJP is performing better than expected: Raichur, Chitradurga, Gulbarga, Bidar, Mysore, North karnataka</p>
                <p>Districts where it’s performing worse than expected: Belgaum, Vijayapura, Bellary, Tumkur, Shimoga</p>
                <p>(Baseline is my assessment from Nov-Dec 17)</p>
                <p>Overall, at this point, 25-26 looks like a realistic figure for the BJP from Mumbai Karnataka. If they want to win the state, these numbers are not enough!</p>
                <p>In Bijapur district, BJP faces different challenges! The chaos that has ensued with the number of contenders in each seat, internal sabotage and fights within the district unit can all jeopardise BJP’s chances! From 1/8 in 2013, it has to win at least 4 to stay in the race!</p>
                <p>Mumbai Karntaka is turning into the real battleground region district by district. BJP is facing issues internal and external and if they’re not sorted in mission mode, it’ll be hard for BJP to cross 26-27 mark from the 50 seats in the region!</p>
                <p>In crucial Belgaum district with 18 seats, although BJP started on a high, internal rifts & too many big leaders all opposed to each other’s interests is hurting the party. It’s more or less Umesh Katthi+Balachandra Jarakiholi vs Laxman Savadi+Jolle couple. Can pull down BJP!</p>
                <p>Of the 18 seats in the district(Belgaum), in 2013, BJP had won 8 seats(+1 KJP+1 BSRCP). If BJP puts up a united front, they can win as much as 13-14 seats! But with current situation, defending even those 10 seats would be hard!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">13 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>In Haveri, it’s a battle of the equals. Resurgent BJP and formidable Congress have locked horns in a very tough fight. Minister Rudrappa Lamani and former MLA and BSY loyalist Nehru Olekar are sweating it out to the last street and village. BJP seems to have a very thin edge!</p>
                <p>One common pattern that I have observed from Belgaum to North Canara to Shimoga to Chitradurga to Davangere to Haveri- Modi’s personal popularity is largely intact and for Loksabha, irrespective of the outcome of assembly elections, BJP is the first choice!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">11 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>Hiriyur is one constituency where Congress and JDS both have had substantial influence with BJP always struggling to make its mark. This time, it’s a tough tripolar contest between Cong’s Sudhakar, BJP’s Shrinivas and JDS’ Manjunath(or whoever that party fields)</p>
                <p>ST reserved Challakere in Chitradurga district is shaping up into an interesting battle. Incumbent MLA T Raghumurthy is facing tough competition from actor Shashikumar for Cong ticket. BJP’s K T Kumaraswamy & JDS’ Patel Tippeswamy are locked in with Con in a tough tripolar!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">10 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>Holalkere in Chitradurga district is a hot battleground seat. Social welfare minister and Siddu’s trusted aide H Anjaneya has become unpopular in the constituency. BSY loyalist, BJP’s M Chandranna has an initial upper hand. Entry of many new candidates has complicated the scene!</p>
                <p>Had to hurry through Bhadravati & Tarikere constituencies. General mood in Bhadravati is very divided between incumbent MLA M J Appaji of JDS & Cong’s B K Sangameshwar. In Tarikere, the general mood is in favour of BJP. It will be an easy win if former MLA Suresh gets BJP ticket!</p>
                <p>Shimoga Rural should’ve been a Prime pick-up seat for BJP this time but due to confusions surrounding the candidate selection is hurting the party. Incumbent JDS MLA Sharada Purya Naik is from the right branch of SCs and is putting up good fight. Only United BJP can defeat her!</p>
                <p>Channagiri in Davangere district is a key swing seat. Incumbent MLA Vadnal Rajanna of Cong faces his traditional rival Madal Virupakshappa of BJP who had lost in 2013 on KJP ticket with a paper thin margin. This time the seat seems to be tilted in favour of BJP!</p>
                <p>Shimoga assembly constituency is witnessing strange political strides. Political Paperweight K B Prasanna Kumar of Congress, who was lucky to win in 2013 purely due to a vertical split in BJP votes is putting up a spirited fight against BJP. BJP’s ranks are still divided!</p>
                <p>BSY loyalist Rudre Gowda & ex Dy CM K S Eshwarappa are at each other’s throats to secure the party ticket from Shimoga city seat. Unless there’s a consensus candidate and entire party works, Prasanna Kumar is not a pushover! Alarm bells for @BSYBJP</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">9 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>Yesterday’s route map that I covered. It was very tiring but a very interesting trail across the green belt of Karnataka. I covered 5 assembly constituencies and touched on 2 more. Khanapur, Haliyal, Yallapur, Sirsi, Soraba, Shikaripura & Sagara! More exciting day ahead</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture29.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <p>Kagodu Timmappa, the tallest minister in Siddu cabinet is so unpopular in his constituency that anyone with brains inside Cong would convince him to not contest! BJP’s ex MLA from Soraba, H Halappa will most likely run from BJP. Ex MLA Gopalkrishna might damage BJP!</p>
                <p>In heart of Malnad- Soraba! Ex CM Bangarappa’a sons have locked horns in a nail biting contest. Kumar fights on BJP ticket while Madhu is the incumbent JDS MLA. Ex BJP MLA Halappa’s backing makes otherwise lacklustre Kumar a strong contender to the seat! Very interesting fight!</p>
                <p>In Sirsi, BJP strongman Vishweshwar Hegde kageri is pitted against Shashibhushan Hegde, grandson of Ramakrishna Hegde in a stiff contest! Kageri has done exemplary works in the constituency and iswidely respected. Split in havyaka Brahmin votes can hurt him though!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">8 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>Haliyal in North Canara district is one of the most prestigious and hottest seats this time! Industries minister and Congress veteran R V Deshpande is facing a very tough fight from BJP’s Sunil Hegde. Despite much development work, Deshpande is facing a lot of heat!</p>
                <p>Early start to the day! In Khanapur, the Marathi bastion of Belgaum. Sitting MLA Arvind Patil of MES has moved towards BJP, Cong fielding wife of ex cop Hemant Nimbalkar. MES to field a fresh face! Tough tripolar contest on cards with an early edge to BJP!</p>
                <p>In Arabhavi, Balachandra Jarakiholi is absolutely undefeatable. Whether he contests on BJP ticket or goes to Cong or fights as an independent, there’s no one in the constituency who can defeat him! Talk in the constituency is that he is suffocated inside BJP.</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">7 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>BJP’s Raju Bharamagouda Kage had won Kagawada General constituency in 2013 against all odds. His opponent Shrimanth Patil who had contested on JDS ticket & lost with thin margin last time is the Cong candidate this time. It’s a tough call with an early edge to Cong!</p>
                <p>Now in BJP strongman Umesh Katthi’s constituency Hukkeri in belgaum district. There’s no election fever here. The result is a long foregone conclusion. He’s absolutely invincible in his constituency!</p>
                <p>In Yamakanamaradi, Belgaum- Cong minister and strongman Satish Jarakiholi’s constituency. BJP has consolidated some ground since I was last here but still difficult to defeat Satish! BJP is tapping his cousin Lakhan Jarakiholi to take on the sugar baron!</p>
                <p>Sugarcane is a big big issue in Belgaum district. As much as Siddu is trying to encash on it, farmers mostly credit central govt for improved pricing & bill settlements. Both parties have hold on sugar factories in the district but Cong(Prakash Hukkeri & Jarakiholis) has an edge.</p>
                <p>Eldest of the Jarakiholis, Ramesh has held Gokak for almost 2 decades. Despite good development track record, It’s a hot battleground seat this time. BJP’s Ashok Pujari is a household name in the constituency now. But Jarakiholis have consolidated over the past month!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">5 Feb 2018</h5>
                <p>In response to Congress’ game of inducting strongmen B Nagendra & Anand Singh, BSY-Sriramulu-Reddy family have played all the right pawns by getting two big shots into BJP. With a sure footed strategy, BJP can win 5-7 seats in Bellary district!</p>
                <p>Royal Family Scion and long time Congress loyalist M Y Ghorpade’s son Kartikeya has now joined BJP. E Tukaram of Cong had won for 3 consecutive terms from Sandur in Bellary district with the support of Ghorpade family. Another good catch for the BJP in Bellary!</p>
                <p>Veteran Congress leader Gaviyappa, ex MLA from Hospet in Bellary district has joined BJP. He was defeated by Anand Singh of BJP in the past two elections. Anand Singh is now in Congress. Complete transposition! The seat has opened up again for the BJP now!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">20 Jan 2018</h5>
                <p>Updated seat ratings for Bijapur district:</p>
                <p>Upgrading Babaleshwar(seat of MB Patil, chief conspirator of Lingayat movement) from toss-up to lean Cong</p>
                <p>Downgrading Muddebihal from Lean Cong to toss-up</p>
                <p>Final figures stand at:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>BJP 3</li>
                    <li>Con 2</li>
                    <li>Toss-up 3</li>
                </ul>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture30.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <p>Updated seat-ratings for Belgaum district. Downgrading Kudachi, Bailhongala, Kittur & Nippani from Safe BJP to lean BJP, downgrading Kagawad from Lean BJP to toss-up, upgrading Yamakanamaradi from Lean Cong to Safe Cong!</p>
                <p>Final figures stand at:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>BJP 12</li>
                    <li>Con 3</li>
                    <li>Toss-up 3</li>
                </ul>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">16 Jan 2018</h5>
                <p>With analysis of all the districts of the state, this is what Karntaka looks like:</p>
                <p>Total seats 224</p>
                <p>Safe BJP 30</p>
                <p>Lean BJP 72</p>
                <p>Toss-up 46</p>
                <p>Lean Cong 49</p>
                <p>Safe Cong 5</p>
                <p>Lean JDS 20</p>
                <p>Safe JDS 2</p>
                <p>(Caution: this contains analysis of many districts from over 2 months ago. Need to be revisited)</p>
                <p>Seat-ratings for Bangalore urban. Almost status-quo since 2013 as it stands today! BJP needs to pull up it’s socks and work really hard if they want to defeat Congress!</p>
                <p>So far it tools like BJP 13, Con 11 & 4 toss-ups!</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture34.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>



                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">5 Jan 2018</h5>
                <p>With its 19 seats, the 3 districts of coastal Karnataka play a crucial role in deciding who ascends to throne in Bangalore. BJP’s erstwhile fortress was thoroughly captured by Cong in 2013. BJP had collapsed to a meagre 3 seats while Cong had swept the region by winning 13 seats</p>
                <p>This was the only region of the state where the BJP had lost the day due to real anger of the electorate against the BJP for failing to give a stable government and not due to the vote-split between BJP & KJP. Congress became the direct beneficiary of the anti-incumbency vote!</p>
                <p>As the Hindutva heartland of the south, this region had given the first base for the BJP and Jansangh before that in Karnataka. BJP has won all 3 Loksabha seats of the coast consistently since 1999. This is the strongest base for Sangh and it’s subsidiaries in the state!</p>
                <p>Demographically, UCs, Billavas, Bunts, Idigas, Devadigas, SCs, Muslims, Christians, STs(in North Canara) form the biggest voting blocs although in this election, religion based voting is likely to transcend caste based pattern!</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture36.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>

                <p>Despite their worst ever drubbing in 2013, BJP performed impressively in the 2014 Loksabha election when they took lead in 17 of the 19 seats(baring Mangalore and Haliyal)</p>
                <p>In the changed political scenario, 5 years later, all the factors which worked for Cong have dissipated. Religious polarisation following murders of more than a dozen Hindu activists and state govt’s friendly treatment of PFI/SDPI has galvanised anger against Congress govt!</p>
                <p>Inability of sitting Cong MLAs to bring many significant Infra projects to the region is also hurting the ruling party along with disconnect of most of the sitting MLAs with the ground.</p>
                <p>Although Cong boasts of tall leaders like RV Deshpande, UT Khader, Ramanath Rai, Vasantha Bangera, Gopal Pujari, Abhayachandra et al, the wrong policies & strategies of Cong have left a large chunk of their cadre/workers disillusioned and disinterested to work for the elections.</p>
                <p>Although BJP starts on high, there are issues that can hurt the saffron party. The disillusionment from the previous tenure of BJP of 2008-13 among voters has still not completely disappeared. BJP faces trust issues in the region when it comes to governance & delivery on promises</p>
                <p>Besides this, BJP also faces problem of too many or no proper candidates on some seats including Udupi, Puttur and Karwar. JDS mostly is a marginal player in the coast and has no base to even retain deposits in any seat in Udupi or South Canara districts!</p>
                <p>In North Canara too, most of the local leaders of JDS have left the party to join BJP including ex MLA of Haliyal Sunil Hegde who had defeated Cong bigwig RV Deshpande in 2008!</p>
                <p>With all that background, here’s an attempt to rate each of the 19 seats of 3 coastal districts. The political scenes in the coast are still evolving and clearer picture will emerge in the coming weeks and as the Election Day nears!</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture37.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture38.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture39.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">4 Jan 2018</h5>
                <p>Very popular and respected BJP MLA Nemiraj Naik had lost this seat by just about 1000 votes in 2013. This is one of the prime pick up seats for the BJP in 2018!</p>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">2 Jan 2018</h5>
                <p>Bellary is one of the bigger districts with a broad geographical spread with its dusty terrain and thatched roads from the huge trucks plying the mine dust, scorching heat, water scarcity and never ending clout of mine bosses in the district politics!</p>
                <p>In 2008, buoyed by the tremendous clout of the Reddy family of Bellary, BJP had swept the district winning 8 of the 9 seats, most seats with big margins! All 8 MLAs were Reddy family loyalists. Cong’s erstwhile bastion was decimated!</p>
                <p>Results of previous assembly elections in Bellary district:</p>

                <p>2004</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>BJP 3</li>
                    <li>JDS 3</li>
                    <li>Con 1</li>
                    <li>Ind 1</li>
                </ul>
                <p>2008</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>BJP 8</li>
                    <li>Con 1</li>
                </ul>
                <p>2013</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Con 4</li>
                    <li>BSR 2</li>
                    <li>BJP 1</li>
                    <li>JDS 1</li>
                    <li>Ind 1</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Demographically, the district has one of the largest ST populations in the state, and sizeable SC population. Only 2 of the 9 seats(Bellary City & Vijayanagara) in the district are unreserved. 5 are reserved for STs and 2 for SCs!!</p>
                <p>Apart from SCs and STs who constitute over 40% of all the voters in the district, Lingayats, Kurubas and Muslims form next big vote blocks. Numerous middle caste groups form the usually floating vote groups which are crucial for the victory of any party/candidate!</p>
                <p>More than party, personal clout of the candidates matters in the district. For e.g., Kudligi MLA B Nagendra has won on BJP ticket and as an independent and this time is looking to fight on Cong ticket, and seems to be the front runner in his constituency irrespective of party!</p>
                <p>Similarly, Vijayanagar MLA Anand Singh, Bellary city MLA Anil Lad, Hadagali MLA PT Parameshwar Naik, Sandur MLA E Tukaram, all mostly win with their personal clout.</p>
                <p>What worked against the BJP in 2013 was that the party was ambandoned by both B Sriramulu who formed his own BSRCP and by Reddy family who remained out of politics as Gali Janardhar Reddy was in jail facing trial in DA cases!</p>
                <p>This time around, B Sriramulu is back in the BJP and the Reddy family is also partly back in the picture trying to influence the choice of candidates in some seats and trying to secure a seat or two for the family itself!</p>
                <p>Cong’s sitting MLAs have become unpopular with the masses as I have observed from my interactions. It’s now sacked Minister PTP Naik of Hadagali is by far the most unpopular! Bellary MLA NY Gopalakrishna is an outsider to the district that won the bypoll after BSR resigned</p>
                <p>Bellary city MLA Santosh lad and Siragupa MLA BM Nagaraj, both mine Barons are on sticky wickets with BSR, Reddy family and BJP all 3 are back in the same mix! Only person seem to be relatively insulated from all this is Sandur MLA Tukaram(who also has his own issues!)</p>
                <p>Possible/winnable candidates from the BJP:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Vijayanagara-Anand Singh</li>
                    <li>Bellary-J Shantha/B Sriramulu himself</li>
                    <li>Bellary city-Somashekhar Reddy</li>
                    <li>Siraguppa-Somalingappa</li>
                    <li>Kampli-Suresh Babu</li>
                    <li>Hadagali-Bhimanaik/Madhunaik</li>
                    <li>HBHalli-Nemirajanaik</li>
                </ul>
                <p>This is how the seats of Bellary district look like as of today: it is completely possible for the BJP to repeat 2008 performance however it cannot he ruled out that Cong might regain some of the ground in coming months and make it an equal game!</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture40.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">30 Dec 2018</h5>
                <p style="text-align: center;">Shimoga Chikmangur analysis</p>
                <p>In 2008, BJP had swept this belt bagging 10 of the 12 seats. In 2004 too, BJP had won 10 seats. It was an unquestionable saffron fortress until 2013 when BSY’s KJP pulled it down to 2 seats! KJP itself had won a seat and had come 2nd in 7 seats!</p>
                <p>The hold that BS Yadyurappa wields in these two districts is unmatched in political history of the region! From APMCs to Panchayatis to ULBs to DCC bank, his followers dominate the political scene in two districts.</p>
                <p>The combination of age old Hindutva, high UC population, high Lingayat population and BSY’s personal clout makes this belt ripe for another BJP sweep. That said, there are inherent challenges too which the saffron party has to address. JDS Top has a sizeable presence here</p>
                <p>BJP suffers from the problem of too many candidates in several constituencies and this might turn out to be a nightmare. Besides that, BJP has no sizeable presence or good candidates in Bhadravati and Kadur seats, incidentally the only seats where BJP is unable to make gains now!</p>
                <p>To everyone’s surprise, JDS had won 5 of the 12 seats in these 2 districts. Baring Bhadravati and Kadur the other three were incidental gains due to vote-split. This time around, JDS might be lucky to retain even one of those 5 seats that it had won on 2013!</p>
                <p>In 2014 Loksabha, BJP had taken unassailable leads in 11 of the 12 constituencies(baring Kadur which falls under Hassan PC where Devegauda was the candidate). In fact even in Bhadravati where BJP has never won as assembly election, BJP got lead of over 10k votes!</p>
                <p>Demographically, Lingayats, Vokkaligas, Dalits and UCs form the biggest vote blocks in Shimoga-Chikmagalur. Large Muslim populations wed influence in Shimoga city, Chikmagalur town and Bhadravati town! Winning combination with the BJP though</p>
                <p>Probable(winnable candidates-based on my travels/interactions) for Shimoga District:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Shimoga-K S Eshwarappa/Rudre Gowda</li>
                    <li>Shimoga Rural-Basavanneppa/KG Kumaraswamy/KE Kanthesh(KSE’s son)</li>
                    <li>Soraba-K Bangarappa/H Halappa</li>
                    <li>Sahara-H Halappa/B Gopalkrishna</li>
                    <li>Thirthahalli- Araga Gnyanendra</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Shikaripura-Anyone that BSY’s anoints/BSY himself</p>
                <p>Bhadravati-None as of now/JDS MLA Appaji is apparently in talks with BJP!</p>
                <p>Chikmagalur-CT Ravi</p>
                <p>Sringeri-Jeevaraj</p>
                <p>Mudigere-MP Kumaraswamy</p>
                <p>Tarikere-DS Suresh</p>
                <p>Kadur-None as of now, BJP has little chance to win this seat!</p>
                <p>With all that background analysis, here’s the seat ratings for Shimoga-Chikmagalur districts. It’s BJP’s battle to lose here! Winning 10/12 is absolutely imperative for the saffron party to gain simple majority in the state!</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture41.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture42.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">27 Dec 2018</h5>
                <p>Davangere District largely heralds the political mood in Karnataka. In 2008, riding on BSY wave, BJP had won 6 of the 8 seats, while in 2013, it was reduced to Zero. KJP had polled twice as many votes as BJP and had lost Channagiri, Mayakonda & Honnali from a striking distance!</p>
                <p>The split in votes between BJP & KJP led to straight Cong victory in 5 of the 8 seats while the 2 Davangere city seats were won default by Cong making its tally a whopping 7/8 with a razor thin, unexpected loss in Harihara to JDS!</p>
                <p>The most notable point about this district is the extent to which Lingayats can singlehandedly decide the winner in most of the seats. Although Cong’s tallest Lingayat leader S Shivashankrappa is from here, his influence is limited to the city. BSY unquestionably overshadows him!</p>
                <p>In 2013, what worked against the BJP has largely been reversed. What worked FOR the Cong has largely been eroded except of course the personal clout of SS & his son in the city! Nearly 100% of all UCs & a significant proportion of OBCs seem have moved towards the BJP!</p>
                <p>One thing that can hurt the BJP though is the disgruntled lot within Old BJP which is miffed with BSY for handing out tickets in most seats to those who came back from KJP- MP Renukacharya(Honnali), Madal Vitupakshappa(Channagiri), BP Harish(Harihara) & SV Ramachandra(Jagalur).</p>
                <p>But it should be borne in mind that these are the only winnable candidates that BJP has in these seats and these internal skirmishes will probably die down closer to the elections. In a way, BSY announcing the candidates early gives them time to sort out issues with rivals!</p>
                <p>As it stands today, Cong stands to lose most of the gains that it made in 2013. Remember, in 2013, BJP did not win any seat and Cong took home 7/8! Here’s what it looks like today</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture43.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>

                <h5 class="blogdate" style="">22 Dec 2018</h5>
                <p style="text-align: center;">Koppal & Raichur Districts</p>
                <p>Koppal & Raichur districts share several common features. A very fractured, volatile & ever changing political atmosphere which almost always is Tripolar/Multipolar, a significant ST & SC population, large Lingayat and Kuruba population and equally large paddy fields are some!</p>
                <p>Even though JDS has lost most of its base in large parts of North Karnataka, these are the two districts where it has retained its influence to an extent. Hence making most seats of Koppal-Raichur madly Tripolar and very difficult to predict!</p>
                <p>In a stiff Tripolar contest in past 3 election cycles, Congress has always emerged as the winner here. BJP’s performance is limited to 3, 4 & 2 seats in 2004, 08 & 13 respectively. JDS has consistently won 1-2 seats in each district while the rest of the seats have been with Cong</p>
                <p>Although candidate selection to a great extent will influence the final outcome, the net movement of Lingayat & ST voters will be decisive. That said, Congress has a strong base of ST-SC-Muslim-Kuruba votebank here!</p>
                <p>BJP has also lost some of its strong leaders like Manappa Vajjal(Lingsugur) to JDS, Pratapgoud Patil(Maski) & Shivraj Tangadagi(Kanakagiri) to Cong. It also faces strong competition from Cong/JDS leaders like Basavaraj Rayareddi(Yalburga), Iqbal Ansari(Gangavati) et al!</p>
                <p>Although it is difficult to predict some of the seats of Koppal-Raichur districts without the clarity about candidates of JDS & BJP, here’s an attempt to rate the 12 seats of these 2 districts!</p>
                <p>(Observe that there are no ‘safe’ seats for any parties- it is that volatile!)</p>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture44.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <div style="text-align: center;"><img style="max-width: 100%;" src="<?= base_url('images/blogs/Picture45.png'); ?>" alt="Crowd Prediction"></div>
                <p>With analysis of 12 districts complete, here’s what seats of Mumbai Karnataka, Hyderabad Karnataka(minus Bellary) & Chitradurga look like:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Total 87 seats</li>
                    <li>Safe BJP 19</li>
                    <li>Lean BJP 27</li>
                    <li>Toss-up 18</li>
                    <li>Lean Cong 17</li>
                    <li>Safe Cong 3</li>
                    <li>Lean JDS 3</li>
                </ul>
                <p>BJP needs to pick up a lot of those toss-up seats!</p>
